Fukei then led forces to confront the Kobun army in several engagements: * '''Ōtagi Mountain (July 3–4):''' Fukei suffered a defeat against {{ill|Ōno no Kaeyasu|ja|大野果安|qq=draft|qq=draft}} but regrouped at Mutsusaka with reinforcements from Mino Province. * '''Rebounding at Ashiike and Nakatsu-michi:''' Fukei’s forces decisively defeated enemy detachments, consolidating control over Yamato Province. * '''Advance to Naniwa (July 22):''' Fukei secured Naniwa and coordinated with regional officials to ensure allegiance to Ōama.
== Death and Legacy == Ōtomo no Fukei passed away on {{nihongo|August 5, 683|Emperor Tenmu12nd year 8月5日|}}. For his contributions during the Jinshin War, he was posthumously granted the Rank of {{ill|Jū Daikin Middle|ja|大錦中|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.<ref>''Shoku Nihongi'', Tenpyō Shōhō 1, 5th intercalary month, 29th day.</ref> His sons, {{ill|Ōtomo no Ushikatsu|ja|大伴牛養|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and {{ill|Ōtomo no Sobei|ja|大伴祖父麻呂|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, continued his lineage, with descendants maintaining prominence in the Nara and Heian periods.
== Genealogy == * '''Father:''' {{ill|Ōtomo no Kujii|ja|大伴咋|qq=draft|qq=draft}} * '''Children:''' ** {{ill|Ōtomo no Ushikatsu|ja|大伴牛養|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (?-749) ** {{ill|Ōtomo no Sobei|ja|大伴祖父麻呂|qq=draft|qq=draft}}
